pacts of the Global Mining Industry -- t10 The Promises and Pitfalls of Pursuing Inclusive, Sustainable Development through Resource Corridors in Africa -- t11 "Community Development" in Oil and Gas Projects: The Case of the West African Gas Pipeline Project -- tSECTION IV Land and Human Security: Central Africa in Focus -- t12 Land, High-Value Natural Resources, and Conflict in the Central African Republic -- t13 Copper Stakes: Exclusion, Corporate Strategies, and Property Rights in the Democratic Republic of Congo -- t14 China and the Democratic Republic of Congo: What the Sicomines Agreement Tells Us about Beijing's Foreign Policy in Africa -- tSECTION V Concluding Remarks and Reflections -- t15 Reflections on Natural Resource-Based Development in Africa in the 2020s -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThere is no question that Africa is endowed with abundant natural resources of different magnitudes. However, more than a decade of high commodity prices and new hydrocarbon discoveries across the continent has led countless international organizations, donor agencies, and non-governmental organizations to devote considerable attention to the potential of natural resource-based development. Natural Resource-Based Development in Africa places a particular emphasis on the actors that help us understand the extent to which resources could be transformed into broader developmental outcomes. Based on a wide variety of primary sources and fieldwork, including in-person interviews and participant observations, this collection contributes to both scholarly and policy discussions around the governance and economic development roles of local entrepreneurs, transnational firms, civil society groups, local communities, and government agencies in Africa's natural resource sectors. Natural Resource-Based Development in Africa explores the impact that these actors have on regional trends such as resource nationalism and local procurement policies as well as grassroots-related issues such as poverty, livelihoods, gender equity, development, and human security.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEconomic developmentzAfrica. 0aNatural resourceszAfricaxManagement. 0aNatural resourceszAfrica. 0aResource cursezAfrica. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  acivil society.  acommunity development.  acorporate social responsibility.  agovernance.  ahuman rights.  amining.  anatural resources and development.  anorms.  aoil and gas.1 aAckah-Baidoo, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkuffo, Edward A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlorse, Raynold Wonder, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrews, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrews, Nathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAwiti, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBassett, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBersaglio, Brock, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaramento, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Andrea M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnns, Charis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFradella, Allyson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab